<h2 class="sk_first">The Machine</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://unknowngenius.com/blog/wordpress/spam-karma" target="_blank">Spam Karma 2</a></strong> is the proud successor to Spam Karma, with whom it shares most of the development ideas, but absolutely none of the code. It is meant to stop all forms of automated Blog spam effortlessly, while remaining as unobtrusive as possible to regular commenters.</p>

<h2>The Man</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://unknowngenius.com/blog/cast/me/" target="_blank">Dr Dave</a></strong> is a card-carrying Evil Genius busy plotting world domination from his volcanic lair in Tokyo, Japan. 
When he is not wasting his time coding ridiculously elaborate anti-spam plugins, he also writes somewhat offensive entries on miscellaneous pointless matters in <a href="http://unknowngenius.com/blog/" target="_blank">his blog</a>.</p>

<h2>The Bribes</h2>
<p>Donations are in <em><a href="http://unknowngenius.com/blog/archives/2004/12/09/buy-me-gifts-im-pretty/" target="_blank">no way</a></em> mandatory: Spam Karma is, first and foremost, a labour of selfless hatred toward this scum of the earth known as spammers. It was originally intended as my modest contribution to the <a href="http://wordpress.org"  target="_blank">Wordpress</a> community effort and the awesome people that make it rock so hard.</p>
<p>Yet, I have been spending considerable amounts of time writing, supporting and debugging both SK1 and SK2. And by massive, believe me, I do mean <em>massive</em>. Therefore, if you like what you see, and want to see more stuff like that in the future, feel free to help me finance my many costly addictions by droping a buck or two in the tip jar...</p>
